# Unity Odin Inspector Preference

- When writing editor code or exposing values/actions in the inspector, actively use Odin Inspector; try an attribute-based solution first.
- If only inspector UX is needed, prefer Odin attributes such as `Title`, `FoldoutGroup`, `BoxGroup`, `TabGroup`, `ShowIf`, `EnableIf`, `ValueDropdown`, and `TableList`; do not write unnecessary custom editors.
- Use `ShowInInspector` for view-only data that should not be persisted; remember that it does not serialize data.
- If data must both be shown and persisted, first check whether Unity serialization is enough; otherwise use `OdinSerialize`, `SerializedMonoBehaviour`, or `SerializedScriptableObject`.
- If an editor window or tool is needed, try `OdinEditorWindow` before writing a plain `EditorWindow`.
- Keep Odin editor code in an `Editor` folder or editor-only assembly; do not leak editor dependencies into runtime assemblies.

## Example

```csharp
public sealed class ExampleAuthoring : SerializedMonoBehaviour
{
    [Title("Runtime Debug")]
    [ShowInInspector, ReadOnly]
    private int ActiveOrderCount => _orderService?.ActiveOrderCount ?? 0;

    [BoxGroup("Config")]
    [Required]
    [SerializeField] private PricingConfig _pricingConfig;
}
```
